ies -- tThe role of universal and targeted family benefits in reducing poverty in single-parent families in different employment situations -- tPolicies and practices for single parents in Iceland -- tThe structural nature of the inadequate social floor for single-parent families -- tReflections and conclusions -- tSocial justice, single parents and their children -- tThe socioeconomics of single parenthood: reflections on the triple bind -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aAvailable Open Access under CC-BY-NC licence. Single parents face a triple bind of inadequate resources, employment, and policies, which in combination further complicate their lives. This book - multi-disciplinary and comparative in design - shows evidence from over 40 countries, along with detailed case studies of Sweden, Iceland, Scotland, and the UK. It covers aspects of well-being that include poverty, good quality jobs, the middle class, wealth, health, children's development and performance in school, and reflects on social justice. Leading international scholars challenge our current understanding of what works and draw policy lessons on how to improve the well-being of single parents and their children.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aBergström, Malin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradshaw, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByun, Young-hwan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalder, Gideon, econtri